<font color="#FF0000">ANSWER TO WINGMAN</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 15 16:27:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tom, point made and well taken.  Like I explained in early post to Art, I seem to have a pre doc and a post doc personality within this site. My early posts were angry and righteous, and when I finally got through, I realized that they were all &quot;tapes&quot;, old anger, old whatever, that I just took out and played 30 years later without examining them first.  Some of the hits I got, and the time I took off to re read and re think, showed me that I had carried alot of crap over the years.  I think that is behind me now.  Voice in the ear, jesus, that does sound preposderous now when I re read it.  Oh well, where I been is where I been.  I'll stand by where I am now.  <br><br>
For reasons I have yet to explore internally, your post (above) moved me alot.  Whether it was your morals, the communal lady, being AWOL, or just the overall sense of confusion that comes out of your soul in your post, touches a place within me too.  While I never doubted that the war was wrong and protesting was the role I HAD to play, the voice in my ear, or soul, was one of fear and terror.  I know many vets found that later in the jungle, I just found it in the good ol USA when the FBI came out to question my parents about their commie son.  It was a time within America that was out of control as well, and that 1A card in my wallet burned like a wanted poster at the Post Office.<br><br>
I'm rambling and I apologize, but I wanted to make the point that viet nam had impacts on us both, you in country, and me not in country.  different as apples and oranges, and I guess the real key here, is to not compare and compete the experiences, just to acknowldge that they both existed...
